# IMP-0600

# Capability SDK Specification

Status: Draft

Version: 0.1

Depends on:

* RFC-0013 Capability Validation Specification
* RFC-0022 Provider Interface
* IMP-0500 Provider SDK

---

# 1. Purpose

This document defines Capabilities as first-class protocol objects.

Capabilities describe executable AI interfaces.

Providers implement Capabilities.

Validators validate Capabilities.

Routers discover Capabilities.

The Hypervisor orchestrates Capabilities.

---

# 2. Design Principles

### CAP-1

Capabilities are protocol objects.

They are not strings.

---

### CAP-2

Every Capability defines a complete execution contract.

---

### CAP-3

Providers implement Capabilities.

Providers do not define Capabilities.

---

### CAP-4

Capabilities are independently versioned.

---

# 3. Capability Definition

Every Capability SHALL define:

```yaml id="jlwmcap1"
capability:

  id:

  version:

  input_schema:

  output_schema:

  billing_unit:

  validation_specification:

  competency_profile:

  supported_streaming:

  supports_batch:

  supports_tools:
```

---

# 4. Capability Identity

Capability IDs SHALL be globally unique.

Examples:

```text id="jlwmcap2"
llm.chat

llm.embedding

speech.tts

speech.stt

vision.caption

vision.detect

image.generate

image.edit

rerank

ocr.document
```

---

# 5. Input Contract

Every Capability SHALL publish its request schema.

Example:

```yaml id="jlwmcap3"
input:

  messages:

  parameters:

  tools:

  metadata:
```

The schema SHALL be machine-readable.

---

# 6. Output Contract

Every Capability SHALL publish its response schema.

Example:

```yaml id="jlwmcap4"
output:

  content:

  finish_reason:

  usage:

  metadata:
```

---

# 7. Billing

Every Capability defines its default Billing Unit.

Examples:

```text id="jlwmcap5"
llm.chat

↓

token
```

```text id="jlwmcap6"
speech.tts

↓

second
```

```text id="jlwmcap7"
image.generate

↓

image
```

The Billing Unit MAY be overridden only through Capability versioning.

---

# 8. Validation

Every Capability references one Validation Specification.

Example:

```text id="jlwmcap8"
llm.chat

↓

CVS-LLM-v2
```

Validators SHALL execute only compatible Validation Specifications.

---

# 9. Competency

Every Capability references one Validator Competency Profile.

Example:

```text id="jlwmcap9"
speech.tts

↓

VCP-TTS-v1
```

A Validator SHALL NOT validate unsupported Capabilities.

---

# 10. Serialization

Capabilities SHALL define:

* request serialization;
* response serialization;
* metadata serialization.

The Hypervisor SHALL remain serialization-independent.

---

# 11. Streaming

Capabilities SHALL explicitly declare:

```yaml id="jlwmcap10"
streaming:

  request:

  response:
```

Streaming support SHALL NOT be inferred.

---

# 12. Extension Fields

Capabilities MAY define optional extensions.

Extensions SHALL remain namespaced.

Example:

```yaml id="jlwmcap11"
extensions:

  openai:

  anthropic:

  custom:
```

Unknown extensions SHALL be ignored.

---

# 13. Compatibility

Providers SHALL publish:

```text id="分快三cap12"
Supported Capabilities
```

Validators SHALL publish:

```text id="cap13"
Supported Validation Profiles
```

Routers SHALL publish:

```text id="cap14"
Supported Capability Versions
```

---

# 14. Versioning

Capability evolution SHALL be additive.

Breaking changes SHALL require a new major Capability version.

---

# 15. Discovery

Endpoint Advertisements SHALL reference Capabilities by identifier and version.

Capability definitions SHALL be discoverable independently from Endpoints.

---

# 16. Design Invariants

Invariant 1

Capabilities are protocol contracts.

---

Invariant 2

Providers implement Capabilities.

---

Invariant 3

Validation belongs to Capabilities.

---

Invariant 4

Billing belongs to Capabilities.

---

Invariant 5

Capabilities evolve independently of Providers.
